    },
    "is_accepted" : true,
    "score" : 428,
    "last_activity_date" : 1576770694,
    "last_edit_date" : 1576770694,
    "creation_date" : 1313093216,
    "answer_id" : 7032144,
    "question_id" : 7032070,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The source code for <code>clear()</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>public void clear() {\n    modCount++;\n\n    // Let gc do its work\n    for (int i = 0; i &lt; size; i++)\n        elementData[i] = null;\n\n    size = 0;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The source code for <code>removeAll()</code>(As defined in <code>AbstractCollection</code>):</p>\n\n<pre><code>public boolean removeAll(Collection&lt;?&gt; c) {\n    boolean modified = false;\n    Iterator&lt;?&gt; e = iterator();\n    while (e.hasNext()) {\n        if (c.contains(e.next())) {\n            e.remove();\n            modified = true;\n        }\n    }\n    return modified;\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><code>clear()</code> is much faster since it doesn't have to deal with all those extra method calls.</p>\n\n<p>And as Atrey points out, <code>c.contains(..)</code> increases the time complexity of <code>removeAll</code> to O(n<sup>2</sup>) as opposed to <code>clear</code>'s O(n).</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 354956,
      "reputation" : 1248,
      "user_id" : 693614,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 64,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b6782906906cd0bf111fe40c3649749a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "CDelaney",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/693614/cdelaney"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1313093237,
    "creation_date" : 1313093237,
    "answer_id" : 7032147,
    "question_id" : 7032070,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>clear() will be much more efficient. It will simply remove each and every item. Using removeAll(arraylist) will take a lot more work because it will check every item in arraylist to see if it exists in arraylist before removing it.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 127578,
      "reputation" : 3129,
      "user_id" : 324851,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4c1ab4accb550fe7b70473548e795055?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Geoff",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/324851/geoff"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 63,
    "last_activity_date" : 1491299485,
    "last_edit_date" : 1491299485,
    "creation_date" : 1313093248,
    "answer_id" : 7032149,
    "question_id" : 7032070,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The time complexity of <code>ArrayList.clear()</code> is <code>O(n)</code> and of <code>removeAll</code> is <code>O(n^2)</code>.</p>\n\n<p>So yes, <code>ArrayList.clear</code> is much faster.</p>\n"
  }, {
